We see that the adjugate A^{*} of A can be computed for any ring (where the components of A^{*} are the minors of A, i.e., (A^{*})_{i,j} equals the determinant of A where we delete row i and column j). Hence
A^{-1}=\frac {1}{\det (A)}A^{*}
which can be computed if \det (A)\in R^{\times }.

Let R=\mathbb {Z}. Let G be an Abelian group. Then there exists s positive integers n_{1}, …, n_{s} and r\in \mathbb {N}_{0} such that
G\cong \mathbb {Z}^{r}\times  Z_{n_{1}}\times …\times  Z_{n_{s}}
where Z_{n_{j}}=\mathbb {Z} / n_{j}\mathbb {Z} is a cyclic group of order n_{j}. Moreover this decomposition is unique up to reordering the factors of finite Abelian groups.

